    "recap_headline": "Troy University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "TROY, Ala.\n- Troy Baseball opened Sun Belt Conference play with a series victory after winning Sunday's rubber match with Old Dominion 9-4 at Riddle-Pace Field.\nThe Trojans (8-11, 2-1 SBC) got five strong innings from junior right-hander\nDylan Alonso\n, who struck out a career-high seven while allowing two runs on three hits and one walk. Troy backed Alonso early, jumping out to a 6-1 lead through the first three innings.\nOld Dominion (9-9, 1-2 SBC) starter JJ Gatti issued two HBPs and two walks in the second inning, allowing Troy to plate its first run, before the Trojans small-balled their way to five runs in the third. After Gatti exited following a pair of leadoff walks, a throwing error to third base on a\nDrew Nelson\nbunt allowed\nZaid Diaz\nto score from second and opened the floodgates.\nBlake Cavill\nfollowed with an RBI single,\nHouston Markham\nadded a sacrifice bunt for another run, and a\nNolan Book\ndouble and\nJosh Pyne\nsingle tacked on two more.\nTroy's bullpen kept the lead intact. Left-hander\nZach Crotchfelt\nstruck out two over two innings, allowing a pair of runs on three hits in the sixth, before right-hander\nCooper Ellingworth\nshut the door with two scoreless frames, striking out three and allowing one hit.\nThe Trojans tacked on some insurance runs with a\nSteven Meier\nRBI single in the fifth, a sacrifice fly from Nelson in the sixth, and another RBI single from Cavill in the eighth.\nNotables\nTroy has opened Sun Belt Conference play with a series win each of the last three seasons.\nTroy moves to 2-1 in rubber matches this season and 12-8 under head coach\nSkylar Meade\n.\nTroy's pitching staff struck out 12 hitters, one shy of its season high.\nDylan Alonso's\nseven strikeouts were the most in his Division-I career. He had previously struck out six hitters against North Alabama while pitching for Middle Tennessee State in 2024.\nIn his first start as a Trojan, Alonso earned his third win of the season. He leads the team in both wins (3) and saves (3).\nTroy's offense drew nine walks, its most this season.\nSteven Meier's\nthree walks tied his career high. He's now done so three times in his career.\nMeier improved his reached base streak to a team-high ten games.\nJosh Pyne\nimproved his hit streak to six games with a 1-for-5 day at the plate.\nZaid Diaz\ndrew four walks, the first Trojan to do so since\nHarrison Bowman\nat Alabama State last season.\nBlake Cavill\nwent 2-for-4 with an HBP and two RBIs. It was both his second multi-hit and second multi-RBI game of the season.\nQuotables\nHead Coach\nSkylar Meade\n\"You look at the last two games, if you want to dive into the pitching aspect, only three walks. No walks yesterday, three walks today. That's a recipe for success on Sundays. Of course,\nDylan Alonso\nset a heck of a tone for what he did. That was great to see.\"\nFirst Baseman\nBlake Cavill\n\"Today was an everybody game. It was a momentum game. An energy game. It's Sunday, the hardest day to win. I think we were loud from the first pitch to the last pitch, and that's what made us win today.\"\nRHP\nDylan Alonso\n\"I just took it one inning at a time. Coach Meade was talking before the game, just think about 1-and-0. I took that on the mound, just make every pitch count.\"\nNext Up\nTroy heads up to Montgomery, Ala., to face Alabama State on Tuesday."
  },
